      <TR>
        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'
 nowrap><b><font color='white' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'>Tenaiya</font></b></td>
        <TD bgcolor='black' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'> Don't bother with dots, I'd say, unless of course the kills go really slowly (no idea of your raid make-up). Go straight for the undead nukes, everything that shares the same graphic type as a normal undead mob will be an undead mob (/rude VI for random Luclin mobs). If HP gets low, tap. I suggest not letting HP get below 40% before tapping. Just be cautious as it's your first trip, you won't learn if you spend too much time dying 8). Besides, you might end up missing all the random messages from the zone.</P><P>I wouldn't bother with charm at level 51 or 47, but if you do intend to, be aware that FD breaks charm.</P><P>There shouldn't be a need to twitch, unless of course you've just had a wipe and there isn't a camped click-stick.</P><P>If you have shamans going along (chances are there will be at least 1), then you probably won't need to use your undead slow, especially if the shammy slow doesn't overwrite it (not sure whether it does, never tested). Shammies are more likely to survive the aggro, plus no point dividing the healers' attention between tanks, shammy and necro.</P><P>I generally don't bother with a pet, because with the sheer numbers of warriors that tend to go along, pet damage isn't terribly significant. Besides, it can be difficult to keep track of the pet when about 15 melees wade in. Anyway, this bit depends on your raid leader (most on the Seventh Hammer won't want pets), and whether you can pay attention to your pet for over 6 hours. Simply put, pets are unnecessary in a Hate raid with 30 people in it. Would be different if it was just 2 groups I guess.</P><P>Tenaiya Soulscorcher</font></td>
      </tr>
